    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3f60f8da_95d94b34",
        "filename": "util/linux/registration_protocol.h",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 32,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-05T22:13:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Do we need to maintain this at registration time? Can’t we just send this along at exception time?",
      "revId": "81643b25486ffdf28d75b5dfdfc028db8f6b02b7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c8e702ac_7017f291",
        "filename": "util/linux/registration_protocol.h",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 35,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-05T22:13:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is subject to forgery. We shouldn’t transfer this with the registration. Instead, we can pick up the client’s PID with SO_PEERCRED.",
      "revId": "81643b25486ffdf28d75b5dfdfc028db8f6b02b7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "be1b2795_eab484e0",
        "filename": "util/linux/registration_protocol.h",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 38,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-05T22:13:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Shouldn’t this be up to the handler to decide too?",
      "revId": "81643b25486ffdf28d75b5dfdfc028db8f6b02b7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "523da591_fdbeceab",
        "filename": "util/linux/registration_protocol.h",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 39,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-05T22:13:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It seems that it’s possible that if the answers to each of the above questions is appropriate, the registration struct becomes empty. At that point, we may not even need it at all. Then we can eschew explicit registration and just allow anyone with access to the correct file descriptor to be a client. Fewer IPCs (at startup, which is heavily performance-sensitive), and less state to maintain in the handler: that’d be a win.\n\nWe couldn’t achieve this on Windows because the mechanism that we use to signal “I’m crashing” was chosen for its reliability and simplicity, which were both critical in a crashing process, and that mechanism does require registration and in-handler state. But I see no reason that we should be limited in the same way on Linux/Android.",
      "revId": "81643b25486ffdf28d75b5dfdfc028db8f6b02b7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    }
  ]
